    "summary": "The Battle of the Metaurus (207 BC) was a crucial Roman victory during the [[event:1054|Second Punic War]] that ended Hasdrubal Barca's attempt to bring reinforcements from Spain to his brother Hannibal in Italy. The defeat crushed the last real hope of Carthaginian strategic success in the war.\n\nHasdrubal had marched an army of around 30,000 across the Alps following Hannibal's route, aiming to link up with his brother in southern Italy. The Roman consuls Gaius Claudius Nero and Marcus Livius Salinator coordinated a rapid strategic movement — Nero made a secret forced march north with part of his army while leaving enough troops in the south to deceive Hannibal — and joined Livius's forces to engage Hasdrubal near the Metaurus River. Hasdrubal was defeated and killed. The Romans sent his severed head south and had it thrown into Hannibal's camp, delivering the news of his brother's death in the most brutal possible fashion. Hannibal reportedly said this foretold Rome's victory, and withdrew to the far south of Italy where he remained for four more years, never able to campaign effectively again, until recalled to Africa.",
